To terminate a C program, you can use several methods depending on the context in which the program is running. Here are some common ways to terminate a C program:

1. **Return from the Main Function**: The most straightforward way to terminate a C program is to return from the `main` function. This is the standard way to signal that the program has finished execution. You can do this by simply returning from the `main` function without any further code.

   ```c
   int main() {
       // Your program code here
       return 0;
   }
   ```

2. **Use `exit()` Function**: You can also use the `exit()` function to terminate the program. This function is part of the C standard library and is used to signal that the program should terminate. However, it is generally not recommended to use `exit()` in the main function, as it can lead to undefined behavior. Instead, use it in a signal handler or a child process.

   ```c
   #include <stdio.h>
   #include <stdlib.h>

   int main() {
       // Your program code here
       exit(0);
       return 0;
   }
   ```

3. **Use `kill()` Function**: If you are running a child process, you can use the `kill()` function to terminate it. This function is part of the C standard library and is used to signal that the child process should terminate. However, it is generally not recommended to use `kill()` in a signal handler, as it can lead to undefined behavior.

   ```c
   #include <stdio.h>
   #include <stdlib.h>
   #include <signal.h>

   int main() {
       // Your program code here
       signal(SIGTERM, handler);
       signal(SIGINT, handler);
       signal(SIGTERM, handler);

       // Start the child process
       pid_t child = fork(&child, NULL, 0);
       if (child == 0) {
           // Parent process
           // ...
       } else {
           // Child process
           // ...
       }

       // Terminate the child process
       kill(child, SIGTERM);
       return 0;
   }
   ```

4. **Use `raise()` Function**: If you are running a child process and want to terminate it using a signal, you can use the `raise()` function to send a SIGTERM signal to the child process. This function is part of the C standard library and is used to signal that the child process should terminate.

   ```c
   #include <stdio.h>
   #include <stdlib.h>
   #include <signal.h>

   int main() {
       // Your program code here
       signal(SIGTERM, handler);
       signal(SIGINT, handler);
       signal(SIGTERM, handler);

       // Start the child process
       pid_t child = fork(&child, NULL, 0);
       if (child == 0) {
           // Parent process
           // ...
       } else {
           // Child process
           // ...
       }

       // Send SIGTERM to the child process
       raise(SIGTERM, 1);

       return 0;
   }
   ```

Remember that terminating a program abruptly can lead to undefined behavior and is generally not recommended unless it is absolutely necessary. It is always better to design your program to terminate gracefully and cleanly.
